Another sword named Ko-Gitsune Maru is housed at [[Isonokami Jingu|Isonokami Shrine]]. As of September 2018, it has been designated a Tangible Cultural Property of [[Nara Prefecture]]<ref name="石上神宮">[http://www.isonokami.jp/about/c4.html ご由緒【宝物】 - 石上神宮]2019th year 11月17日閲覧</ref><ref name="奈良県">[http://www.pref.nara.jp/secure/143530/kenshiitiran.pdf 奈良県指定文化財一覧 - 奈良県（PDF版）]2019th year 11月17日閲覧</ref>. According to its legend, it was stolen during the late Edo period from the [[Emperor Suinin Mausoleum]] by grave robbers and sold to [[Takatsukasa Masamichi]], who, upon discovering its origin, donated it to the shrine{{sfn|かみゆ歴史編集部|2015|p=56-57}}. The blade bears the signature of “Yoshinori,” attributed to the [[Ko-Bizen school]]{{sfn|かみゆ歴史編集部|2015|p=56-57}}.
